class Solution {
public:
    int countNodesinLoop(ListNode *head) {
        ListNode *slow = head;
        ListNode *fast = head;

        while(fast != NULL && fast->next != NULL){

            slow = slow->next;
            fast = fast->next->next;

            if(slow == fast){

                int count = 1;

                fast = fast->next;

                while(slow != fast){
                    count++;
                    fast = fast->next;
                }

                return count;
            }
        }

        return 0;
    }
};
Interview Explanation
Step 1

"First, I detect the cycle using slow and fast pointers."

Step 2

"Once both pointers meet, I know they are inside the loop."

Step 3

"I keep one pointer fixed and move the other pointer one step at a time."

Step 4

"I count every step until it reaches the same node again."

Step 5

"The count gives the length of the loop."

Easy Notes
1. Detect cycle.

2. Both pointers meet.

3. Keep one pointer fixed.

4. Move the other pointer.

5. Count until it comes back.

6. Return count.
⭐ Memory Trick (All Three Problems)
Detect Cycle
↓
Fast catches Slow

-------------------

Find Start
↓
One pointer → Head
One pointer → Meeting Point
Move both one step
Meet = Start

-------------------

Find Loop Length
↓
After meeting
Move one pointer around the loop
Count steps

These three problems all use the same Floyd's Slow and Fast Pointer technique. The only difference is what you do after the slow and fast pointers meet:

Detect Cycle: Return true.
Find Start of Cycle: Reset one pointer to head, then move both one step until they meet.
Find Loop Length: Count the number of nodes in the cycle by moving one pointer around the loop.
